Two files to fix:

1. docs/content/docs/guides/plugin-development.mdx — line ~431:
```typescript
const data = await fetchJSON("/api/items");
log.debug("Got response", { count: data.items.length });
return { items: data.items };
```
This has no type parameter at all (data is unknown | undefined), and then accesses data.items. Add a type parameter and null-check: `const data = await fetchJSON<{ items: Item[] }>('/api/items', undefined); if (!data) throw ToolError.internal('No data'); log.debug('Got response', { count: data.items.length });`

2. docs/content/docs/guides/logging-debugging.mdx — lines ~82-83:
```typescript
const results = await fetchJSON(`/api/search?q=${encodeURIComponent(query)}`);
log.info('Search complete', { resultCount: results.items.length });
```
Same issue — no type parameter and no null check. Add a type annotation and null-check.

IMPORTANT: These are code blocks inside MDX files. The surrounding text/prose context matters — make sure the fix fits naturally within the explanatory paragraph. Do not change non-code portions of the file.

File: docs/content/docs/sdk/resources.mdx

Only 1 instance to fix. Lines 223-229 in the 'Resource Templates' example:
```typescript
const data = await fetchJSON<{ channels: Array<{ id: string; name: string; is_private: boolean }> }>(
  '/api/conversations.list?types=public_channel,private_channel',
);
return {
  uri,
  text: JSON.stringify(data, null, 2),
```
data could be undefined. JSON.stringify(undefined) returns undefined (not a string), which would produce an invalid ResourceContent.

The same file already has a correct pattern at lines 183-189 (the 'Basic Resource' example uses `if (!data)` guard). Follow that exact pattern for consistency within the file:
```typescript
if (!data) {
  return { uri, text: '[]', mimeType: 'application/json' };
}
```
or similar fallback.
